Table 1 shows the comparison among PRUF, APRUF, PRW and DW [26, 28] algorithms. For all four algorithms 8-pixel and 4-pixel neighbourhoods were considered.
For both C4L and BSDS500, APRUF (4-pixel on GPU-c) is the fastest: 0.37ms for the smallest image group (256×256256256256{\times}256256 × 256) and 5.56ms for the largest image group (2560×1920256019202560{\times}19202560 × 1920).
APRUF’s improvement over DW is between 41.44% and 67.52%.
PRUF (fastest) shows a 44.21% improvement over APRUF (slowest) for the 4000×4000400040004000{\times}40004000 × 4000 images, indicating effectiveness of the reduction rate on larger images (detailed analysis in [13]).
The comparison of the execution times among the 8-neighbour implementations of the algorithms shows a pattern similar to the case of 4-neighbour implementations discussed above.

S6.T5.60.caption: Table 5:  Comparison of CEGCN with different superpixel segmentation methods vs waterfall method
references:
In the setting of CEGCN, we compare waterfall against superpixel algorithms: SLIC [45], quick shift (QS) [46], Felzenszwalb and Huttenlocher’s (FH) method [47], linear spectral clustering (LSC) [1], and SEEDS [48]. The comparison is conducted on three different HS images: Indian Pines, University of Pavia, and Salinas [44]. Each experiment is repeated ten times, reporting overall accuracy (OA), average accuracy (AA), and kappa coefficient (κ𝜅\kappaitalic_κ) and the training time. All the superpixel segmentation methods use the hyperparameters provided in [44]. The waterfall algorithm (4-connectivity with 𝑁𝐿=4𝑁𝐿4\mathit{NL}{=}4italic_NL = 4 for Indian Pines, University of Pavia datasets and 8-connectivity with 𝑁𝐿=3𝑁𝐿3\mathit{NL}{=}3italic_NL = 3 for Salinas dataset) is applied on the gradient magnitude of the compressed images after applying Gaussian blurring. The compressed image of the HSI is constructed by averaging values of all spectral bands. As proposed in [44], superpixel algorithms are executed on the HSI prepossessed using linear discriminant analysis (LDA). We found that skipping the preprocessing steps improved the results of the waterfall.
Table 5 reports that the waterfall outperforms the other algorithms.
The waterfall regions tend to be larger, thus they help speed up the training without loss of accuracy.

We compare waterfall to SLIC on the ISIC (skin) and JSRT (lung, heart, clavicle) datasets (cropped as per [2]), with the mild label noise setting (noise ratio α=0.3𝛼0.3\alpha{=}0.3italic_α = 0.3, noise level β=0.5𝛽0.5\beta{=}0.5italic_β = 0.5).
We evaluate the predicted masks with Dice similarity coefficient (DSC) [49] averaged over the last 10 epochs (out of 200).
Hyperparameters of SLIC are as described in [2]. Waterfall is applied on the gradient magnitude of the images with: 4-connecitivity for ISIC, JSRT lung, 8-connectivity for JSRT clavicle and heart; 𝑁𝐿=4𝑁𝐿4\mathit{NL}{=}4italic_NL = 4 for JSRT and 𝑁𝐿=2𝑁𝐿2\mathit{NL}{=}2italic_NL = 2 for ISIC. Training times and DSC scores are reported in Table 6.
